<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/kha_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/kha_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Madison WI Misty Mountain 4/2/2002<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.62)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8714'>Xanthix "Xanthix" Xanthix</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8714&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 2, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Tournament Report<br>
4/2/2002<br>
Misty Mountain Game Shop Tuesday Night Tournament<br>
<br>
So I return to Misty Mountain for my second LOTR tournament. It&#39;s the week after Spring Break and I&#39;m up for some LOTR play, plus the grand prize is a foil rare Balrog this time. This draws a big crowd for a Tuesday night tournament, and twelve people enter the tournament. That means that this tourney can be sanctioned, unlike the last one I made. So now I have a Decipher rating!<br>
<br>
Anyway, I&#39;ve been preparing for the tournament for a few days, sorting my Mines of Moria cards and building a deck that I think will be good for the metagame (Fellowship archery and Sauron tricks are popular here). I decide on Dwarves and Uruk-hai. I have lots of Dwarf cards, and Isengard minions are resilient to archery. I also add in some Secret Tech Cards (TM): Spies of Saruman, Their Arrows Enrage, Uruk-hai Armory, (all anti-archery) and Here Lies Balin, Son of Fundin (kill the orcs so Bowmen doesn&#39;t work, and great against Moria). All but one of these turn out to be sub-optimal choices, but one of them does well (read on to find out which). Apart from the Secret Tech the deck is just Dwarf possessions and big Uruk-hai. Anyway, here we go:<br>
<br>
<br>
Game 1: Chris<br>
<br>
Chris is playing a deck similar to the one I swarmed last time when I got lucky. His fellowship is elves and men, and his shadow is - surprise! - Under the Watching Eye/Bowmen/Hate. We get off to good start, me with Dwarf possessions and him with Orophin, then Celeborn, then Galadriel (Orophin is the one that shoots Uruk-hai. Ratio of Orophin sightings to Rumil sightings last tourney, when I was playing orcs: 0:2. Ratio this time: 2:0. Sigh). Things turn for the worse when Gimli gets wounded or UTWE-exerted (can&#39;t remember), and is double-Hated before I have any Endurance of Dwarves on him. Gloin is understandably broken up about this, being Gimli&#39;s dad and all, and decides it&#39;s not worth living anymore. Naturally, Fror takes this pretty hard too and pretty soon Frodo&#39;s all alone with Farin. In the meantime, Gladriel&#39;s Mirror is discarding my shadow hands. First is ditches junk like Goblin Men and Hand Axes, but pretty soon Galadriel gets it focused right and yanks my big dudes. The Uruk-hai that hit the table just aren&#39;t enough to threaten the fellowship, but my fellowship gets killed when Farin is made strength -8 from Enduring Evil so it doesn&#39;t matter.<br>
<br>
Result: Full Loss (1 point)<br>
<br>
Game 2: James<br>
<br>
James looks like one of the guys that just came for the Balrog, but I&#39;m not sure. My early Goblin Man shows me his hand is Goblin Runners, some random Uruks, Athelas, etc, so I&#39;m thinking &quot;scrub.&quot; Later, as he plays Aragorn and Boromir and their weapons and wrecks me with Lurtz, I&#39;m thinking, &quot;...then again, maybe not!&quot; But I&#39;m getting ahead of myself. He starts with Sam and Arwen, fetching Aragorn, and playing out their possessions steadily. He also plays 3 Athelas in the first 2 turns because he drew it all. This has no bearing on the game but I thought it was funny to see Aragorn so stocked with weed. He also plays Orophin, informing me that there&#39;s only one in his deck. Lucky me! His shadow side turns out to be Uruk-hai with pumpers (Lurtz&#39;s Battle Cry and Savagery to Match Their Numbers), Messengers, and Snows, with 4 Goblin Runners thrown in for twilight. My Dwarves are apparently still reeling from their last defeat and they come up short by 1-2 strength in lots of Uruk skirmishes. In a highlight, Gimli kills a Lurtz in one mighty blow, but on the other hand I also make some boneheaded plays and lose 2 Dwarves unnecessarily. Saruman&#39;s Snows seems to come up exactly when he has a Messenger out and when I need the skirmish event I just drew to survive the skirmishimmerhink this ends with Gimli and Frodo bravely standing ofeasterlingainst two 9-strength Uruks. Gimli lives, but poor Frodo is overwhelmed.<br>
<br>
Result: Full Loss (2 points)<br>
<br>
Game 3: Bye<br>
<br>
Some people dropped, one to teach new players the game, and others because they were losing. So I get a bye, my biggest win of the tourney. I sit and ponder about my deck and what&#39;s wrong with it. My conclusions follow this report.<br>
<br>
Result: Bye (5 points)<br>
<br>
Game 4: Todd<br>
<br>
Todd is a Saturday regular, here because of the Balrog&#39;s turnout. Apparently no one told him that the Tuesday metagame that I prepared for was Orcs/Bowmen, and he is playing Uruk-hai too. His fellowship is mains and toys (and pipes, interestingly), complete with Armor (Armor basically says &quot;All Uruk-hai are now Damage -1, Scariness -4, and Effectiveness -10.&quot; Number of decks I saw running Armor last tourney: 1. Number this time: 3. Sigh). I don&#39;t even want to say what Todd&#39;s fighting Uruk-hai did to my Dwarves. It was too horrible. The Dwarves stood brave and proud, but their Hand Axes dropped in vain and their weapons had no effect on Troops of Uruk-hai. Gimli killed Lurtz again, but Lurtz&#39;s elite Uruk-hai bodyguard team slaughtered my other Dwarves. I used Realm of Dwarrowdelf to win some skirmishes, at the cost of burning through half my deck, but it was no use and Frodo died. On the bright side, I got to play 3 Their Arrows Enrage, meaning that Aragorn was strength -3. Todd forgot this twice and Aragorn lost the skirmishes as a result. But Aragorn uses protection - he was wearing Armor the whole game and shrugged off the damage by smoking his pipe.<br>
<br>
Result: Full Loss (6 points)<br>
<br>
At this point, the tournament was concluded, since the store&#39;s closing time was approaching. I for one was glad - I don&#39;t know who I could have played against next that would have been a worse matchup for me. Chris (matchup 1) won the tournament, and the rare foil Balrog. I&#39;m happy for him - he&#39;s a great guy to play against. As for me, I think I got like 9th place overall, getting 1 pack as a prize. The rare was junk, as were the three rares in the Gandalf starter I bought after because I needed Gandalfs. Sigh. On to less depressing topics, let&#39;s do some props and slops, and deck analysis.<br>
<br>
<br>
Props and Slops<br>
<br>
Props:<br>
Chris, James, and Todd, for being great players and very nice too.<br>
Bye, for letting me win a match.<br>
Their Arrows Enrage, for winning the Most Likely To Be A Good Card If Used In A Deck Not Played By Me award.<br>
Misty Mountain, for being the best card shop I know of.<br>
<br>
Slops:<br>
Randomness, for pairing me against decks the opposite of what I metagamed for.<br>
The Balrog: [BEGIN SIDE RANT] I ran a Balrog in case I had nothing at the Bridge. I drew him all three games. In one game I drew him at site 4, couldn&#39;t play him at 5, and then had no Uruk-hai in my hand at site 6, with 16 twilight available. I played the stupid Balrog at site 6 (automatically discards self) just to get it out of my hand. Grrr! Darn Balrog! [END SIDE RANT]<br>
<br>
<br>
Analysis Of Why My Deck Stunk<br>
<br>
So during my bye and in the car on the way home, I thought about my deck&#39;s poor performance (Yes, I realize I have no life. I live vicariously through images of fictional characters on small pieces of cardboard). Here are my thoughts, so that maybe some reader may not make the same mistakes.<br>
<br>
Problems with my deck:<br>
- No card drawing. Other decks used Elrond or Gandalf (Grey Pilgrim); I have nothing.<br>
- No healing (apart from Sanctuaries). Dwarves only have 3 vitality!<br>
- No answer to Uruk-hai. Gimli&#39;s Helm could have helped.<br>
- Dependence on possessions. With 4 possessions, Gimli = Aragorn. Without, Gimli = Dwarf Guard.<br>
- Lack of pump cards. I took out 4 Axe Strike and 2 Flurry of Blows for more toys, and I regretted it a lot.<br>
- Bad choices for Secret Tech Cards. Uruk-hai Armory is overrated, and Here Lies Balin is useless in some matchups. Also, I had too much Uruk-hai tech and not enough meat. Bred for Battle or Savagery would have helped. Maybe Beyond the Height of Men would work for Armor?<br>
- I ignored the moral from my first tourney: &quot;Be ready for Archery.&quot; (Elven Cloaks or Mithril Coat)<br>
<br>
Possible Solutions:<br>
- Splash Aragorn for healing (signet, Athelas) and his strength. I can also pull him when others start the Pony.<br>
- Splash Elves for Elrond, archery, Elven Cloaks.<br>
- Try less tech, more consistency in deck theme.<br>
<br>
However, I probably won&#39;t be able to use all this, because I&#39;m going to try a different decktype next week. Anyway, those are my thoughts. If you&#39;re still here, thanks for reading. I&#39;m mostly writing for fun, but if anyone else can get something out of this, then I&#39;ll feel that I haven&#39;t wasted the evening getting beat up with my Dwarves. Thanks to all who came to the tourney, and see you next Tuesday!<br>
<br>
